The free enthalpy or Gibbs energy (G) is considered a criterion for the spontaneity of a reaction and is negative for any spontaneous chemical reaction [80]. If a reversible reaction is considered, as is the case for fuel synthesis from CO2 and H2, the Gibbs energy can be used as a measure of the chemical equilibrium; see [69]. The total Gibbs energy (GM) of a mixture is defined by the sum of the chemical potentials of all participating species N [80].
6GM=∑j=1Nnjμj\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ {G}_{\mathrm{M}}=\sum \limits_{\mathrm{j}=1}^{\mathrm{N}}{\mathrm{n}}_{\mathrm{j}}{\upmu}_{\mathrm{j}} $$\end{document}with GT: [J]; ni: molar number of species i [mol]; μi: chemical potential of species i [J/mol]. Gibbs energy can be calculated for each species by the following:
7Gj=Hj−TSj\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ {G}_j={H}_j-T\ {S}_j $$\end{document}

